  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_195",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Replicated state machines without replicated execution",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Jonathan Lee",
        "email": "srinath@microsoft",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Kirill Nikitin",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Srinath Setty",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "This paper introduces a new approach to reduce end-to-end costs in large-scale\nreplicated systems built under a Byzantine fault model. Specifically, our\napproach transforms a given replicated state machine (RSM) to another RSM where\nnodes incur lower costs by delegating state machine execution: an untrusted\nprover produces succinct cryptographic proofs of correct state transitions\nalong with state changes, which nodes in the transformed RSM verify and apply\nrespectively.\n\nTo realize our approach, we build Piperine, a system that makes the proof\nmachinery profitable in the context of RSMs. Specifically, Piperine reduces the\ncosts of both proving and verifying the correctness of state machine execution\nwhile retaining liveness—a distinctive requirement in the context of RSMs. Our\nexperimental evaluation demonstrates that, for a payment service, employing\nPiperine is more pro table than naive reexecution of transactions as long as\nthere are $>10^4$ nodes. When we apply Piperine to ERC-20 transactions in\nEthereum (a real-world RSM with up to $10^5$ nodes), it reduces per-transaction\ncosts by $5.4\\times$ and network costs by $2.7\\times$.",
    "keywords": [
      "verifiable computing",
      "zkSNARKs",
      "blockchain",
      "replicated state machines"
    ],
    "category": "Implementation",
